WEBVTT

00:01.253 --> 00:02.753
(upbeat march plays)

00:02.787 --> 00:05.422
♪ Good morning, USA!

00:05.457 --> 00:09.360
♪ I got a feeling that it's
gonna be a wonderful day ♪

00:09.394 --> 00:12.329
♪ The sun in the sky
has a smile on his face ♪

00:12.364 --> 00:16.767
♪ And he's shining a salute
to the American race ♪

00:18.637 --> 00:22.039
♪ Oh, boy, it's swell to say

00:22.073 --> 00:24.041
♪ Good...
♪ Good morning, USA

00:24.075 --> 00:34.267
<font color="#ec14bd">Sync & corrections by honeybunny</font>
<font color="#ec14bd">www.addic7ed.com</font>

00:34.786 --> 00:36.153
This is some party!

00:36.187 --> 00:37.588
Hideki's doing it right.

00:37.622 --> 00:39.390
He's doing it exactly right.

00:39.424 --> 00:42.259
This is one of the craziest
parties I've ever been to.

00:42.294 --> 00:44.562
And as you know,
I'm friend..I'm friendly.

00:44.596 --> 00:47.231
I'm friendsly with Shaun White.

00:50.602 --> 00:52.603
Oh, my God.

00:52.637 --> 00:55.673
Is that... Donna
Nicole Marie Banelli?

00:55.707 --> 00:58.909
Hey, Banelli, you got a lot
of nerve showing up here!

00:58.944 --> 01:00.444
WOMAN:
So what? So what?

01:00.478 --> 01:02.880
It's a free world.
So what?

01:02.914 --> 01:04.415
Excuse me, Stan.

01:04.449 --> 01:08.018
That's the bitch who gave all
my ideas to Michael Crichton.

01:08.053 --> 01:10.020
Hideki!
Happy birthday, man!

01:10.055 --> 01:11.655
You're doing it just right!

01:11.690 --> 01:13.157
This party,

01:13.191 --> 01:15.960
that double-breasted jacket
you're wearing with corduroys,

01:15.994 --> 01:17.328
the '70s pornography

01:17.362 --> 01:19.163
you're projecting
on the wall outside.

01:19.197 --> 01:20.531
These two things here.

01:20.565 --> 01:23.233
These are the last two
Etruscan urns in existence.

01:23.268 --> 01:26.670
Geez, Hide, how do you do it?

01:26.705 --> 01:30.007
You can have anything you want
if you just trust your gut.

01:30.041 --> 01:31.475
I don't always understand

01:31.509 --> 01:33.844
why my gut is telling me
to do something,

01:33.878 --> 01:38.616
but I always do it, because
it has never steered me wrong.

01:38.650 --> 01:40.417
(stomach grumbles loudly)

01:41.720 --> 01:44.088
Oh, my God,
you destroyed one of the urns!

01:44.122 --> 01:47.358
Making this one the
last one in existence.

01:47.392 --> 01:48.659
It's priceless now!

01:48.693 --> 01:50.427
Ha, that's right.

01:50.462 --> 01:52.563
Thank you, gut.

01:53.965 --> 01:55.265
So, what happened?

01:55.300 --> 01:56.634
Eh, wasn't her.

02:00.205 --> 02:03.974
And now, the final Lego
to complete our official entry

02:04.009 --> 02:06.944
into the tri-county
Lego competition!

02:06.978 --> 02:09.947
The four stages of Ron Howard.

02:09.981 --> 02:12.216
STEVE:
Opie, Richie Cunningham

02:12.250 --> 02:14.318
and Ron Howard,
the director <i>with...</i>

02:14.352 --> 02:15.886
and without hat.

02:15.920 --> 02:17.221
Not bad.

02:17.255 --> 02:19.957
I love it, and I still don't
know who Ron Howard is.

02:19.991 --> 02:21.425
What, are you an idiot?

02:21.459 --> 02:23.227
He's only one
of the most popular

02:23.261 --> 02:25.496
mainstream directors
of our time.

02:25.530 --> 02:27.231
Eh, Ron Howard's okay,

02:27.265 --> 02:28.666
but I prefer indie films.

02:28.700 --> 02:29.900
(sniffs)

02:29.934 --> 02:31.068
(sniffing)

02:31.102 --> 02:32.236
Wait a minute.

02:32.270 --> 02:33.637
Do you smell that?

02:33.672 --> 02:37.141
Corned beef, tongue,
whitefish salad.

02:37.175 --> 02:38.575
Oh, no.

02:38.610 --> 02:39.810
A deli platter.

02:39.844 --> 02:42.646
That can only mean one thing.

02:43.782 --> 02:46.250
Mom, who died?

02:46.284 --> 02:48.686
Schmuely.

02:48.720 --> 02:50.387
Uncle Ira?

02:50.422 --> 02:52.856
What are you doing here?

02:52.891 --> 02:54.258
How shall I put this?

02:54.292 --> 02:55.693
You're a child,

02:55.727 --> 02:58.395
and you're gonna remember this
for the rest of your life,

02:58.430 --> 03:00.798
so I want to make sure
I say this right.

03:00.832 --> 03:03.434
(shouting):
Your dad is dead!

03:03.468 --> 03:07.738
He's dead!

03:10.275 --> 03:12.242
Man, that Hideki does it right.

03:12.277 --> 03:13.977
What a perfect party.

03:14.012 --> 03:16.013
Well, not entirely perfect.

03:16.047 --> 03:18.082
The cake?
You noticed, too?

03:18.116 --> 03:20.150
ROGER: <i>Don't you hate it
when you're at a party</i>

03:20.185 --> 03:22.753
<i>and you have to wait, like,</i>
<i>forever for a piece of cake?</i>

03:22.787 --> 03:24.421
STAN: <i>Yeah, but they have
to cut the cake somehow.</i>

03:24.456 --> 03:25.889
<i>But what if they didn't?</i>

03:25.924 --> 03:27.444
<i>You mean, what if</i>
<i>they got enough cakes</i>

03:27.459 --> 03:29.560
<i>to give each and every</i>
<i>person their own entire cake?</i>

03:29.594 --> 03:31.462
<i>No, that's not what</i>
<i>I'm talking about at all.</i>

03:31.496 --> 03:34.531
<i>I mean, what if there was some</i>
<i>way to cut all the pieces...</i>

03:34.566 --> 03:35.933
ROGER and STAN:
<i>At the same time?</i>

03:35.967 --> 03:37.067
STAN:
<i>Like some sort of...</i>

03:37.102 --> 03:38.402
ROGER:
<i>Gridded wire blade system</i>

03:38.436 --> 03:39.937
<i>that could quickly</i>
<i>and conveniently...</i>

03:39.971 --> 03:41.572
<i>Dice the cake into</i>
<i>appropriately-sized pieces</i>

03:41.606 --> 03:42.873
<i>with one simple cut?</i>

03:42.907 --> 03:44.441
<i>Yes! It could even be</i>
<i>dishwasher-safe,</i>

03:44.476 --> 03:45.676
<i>and the wire blades could...</i>

03:45.710 --> 03:47.244
<i>Roll into the handles</i>

03:47.278 --> 03:49.079
<i>so it would fit in a kitchen drawer for...</i>
<i>Easy...</i>

03:49.114 --> 03:50.354
- <i>No...</i>
- <i>Nonsense...</i> - <i>Storage?</i>

03:50.381 --> 03:51.648
<i>We could call it</i>
<i>"Piece of Cake"</i>

03:51.683 --> 03:53.317
<i>because it makes</i>
<i>cutting a piece of cake...</i>

03:53.351 --> 03:54.718
<i>A piece of cake!</i>

03:54.753 --> 03:55.919
(Stan's stomach grumbles loudly)

03:55.954 --> 03:57.087
What was that?

03:57.122 --> 03:58.956
I think that
was... my gut.

03:58.990 --> 04:01.358
Oh, my God, this
is just like Hideki!

04:01.392 --> 04:03.327
If we listen to it,
we'll get rich!

04:03.361 --> 04:04.995
Do you really think
it could work?

04:05.029 --> 04:06.309
(Roger's stomach
grumbles loudly)

04:06.331 --> 04:08.232
I think someone does.

04:08.266 --> 04:09.433
(both stomachs grumbling
in harmony)

04:09.467 --> 04:12.169
They need to be together.

04:12.203 --> 04:13.737
(grumbling nearby)

04:13.772 --> 04:15.172
What's that?

04:15.206 --> 04:17.507
Need an investor?

04:18.976 --> 04:20.878
Oh, my God,
we're really doing this!

04:20.911 --> 04:22.579
I know, it's really
gonna happen!

04:22.614 --> 04:24.648
And the best part is we'll be...

04:24.682 --> 04:27.851
equal partners.

04:27.886 --> 04:30.788
With only a verbal contract
based on trust.

04:30.822 --> 04:33.590
What more is necessary
among friends?

04:33.625 --> 04:35.626
(maniacal laughter)

04:37.195 --> 04:39.196
(stomach growling intensifies)
(car alarm blaring)

04:45.336 --> 04:46.303
Snot?

04:46.337 --> 04:47.704
Wh-What are you doing here?

04:47.739 --> 04:49.373
Why aren't you
at your dad's funeral?

04:49.407 --> 04:50.707
I'm not going.

04:50.742 --> 04:53.544
You're not going
to your own dad's funeral?

04:53.578 --> 04:55.345
It's all the way in Stockton.

04:55.380 --> 04:56.747
And my mom isn't going.

04:56.781 --> 04:58.482
And besides,
I didn't even know him.

04:58.516 --> 05:01.118
At best, we were... "friendsly."

05:01.152 --> 05:03.554
Now, come on, we're gonna be
late for the Lego competition.

05:03.588 --> 05:04.721
Whoa, whoa.

05:04.756 --> 05:06.657
You're not going
to the Lego competition.

05:06.691 --> 05:08.792
Snot, if you don't go
to your dad's funeral,

05:08.827 --> 05:10.961
you're gonna regret it
for the rest of your life.

05:10.995 --> 05:12.830
Like when I cut off
my rat tail.

05:12.864 --> 05:14.832
Steve, this is not
a big deal to me.

05:14.866 --> 05:16.200
I really don't care.

05:16.234 --> 05:18.202
Because you're in denial.

05:18.236 --> 05:20.337
Hmm, how do I make this
clear to you?

05:22.207 --> 05:23.207
Opie!

05:23.241 --> 05:24.708
What the hell, Steve?

05:24.742 --> 05:25.709
New plan.

05:25.743 --> 05:27.311
Barry, how much gas you got?

05:27.345 --> 05:28.879
A half tank,
but it's a big tank.

05:28.913 --> 05:29.980
Why?

05:30.014 --> 05:33.383
Because we're going
to California.

05:33.418 --> 05:36.220
We're taking Snot
to his dad's funeral.

05:36.254 --> 05:38.255
I said I don't want to go.

05:38.289 --> 05:39.857
Snot, come on.

05:39.891 --> 05:41.358
You know what you
would do right now

05:41.392 --> 05:43.160
if this were one
of your indie movies.

05:43.194 --> 05:44.728
You'd drop everything
you were doing,

05:44.762 --> 05:47.331
hop in this car
and take a cross-country trip

05:47.365 --> 05:49.700
to your estranged
father's funeral.

05:49.734 --> 05:51.235
And you know
where your best friends

05:51.269 --> 05:53.370
in the whole world are gonna be?

05:53.404 --> 05:56.673
Right there beside you
every step of the way.

05:58.209 --> 06:00.944
I care about you way too much

06:00.979 --> 06:02.613
to let you miss something
this big.

06:02.647 --> 06:04.448
Fine, but I'm telling you,

06:04.482 --> 06:07.451
I'm gonna get to that funeral
and still not feel anything

06:07.485 --> 06:08.886
about my dad dying.

06:08.920 --> 06:12.222
I promise you, buddy,
by the time we get there,

06:12.257 --> 06:14.958
you're gonna be
an emotional wreck.

06:14.993 --> 06:16.727
♪

